\title{Vivarium Network Topology: Discovered Infrastructure}
\taxon{experiment}
\author{barton-rhodes}
\date{2026-04-08}
\import{macros}
\tag{network}
\tag{vivarium}
\tag{thread}
\tag{zigbee}
\tag{matter}
\tag{discovery}
\meta{scope}{infrastructure}
\meta{device-count}{52}

\p{Empirical network discovery at Vivarium (San Francisco). 52 devices on a flat /24 LAN with no VLAN isolation. Three mesh protocols already active: Thread 1.3 (Apple), Zigbee (Hue), and Wi-Fi. This inventory feeds the alterstructure design (\ref{bcf-0055}).}

\subtree{\title{Mesh Networks}
\taxon{finding}

\table{
\tr{\th{Protocol}\th{Coordinator}\th{IP}\th{Version}\th{Coverage}}
\tr{\td{Thread}\td{Apple HomePod/TV}\td{192.168.0.231}\td{1.3.0}\td{Matter-native mesh, border router}}
\tr{\td{Zigbee}\td{Philips Hue Bridge v2}\td{192.168.0.163}\td{BSB002}\td{Hue ecosystem lighting}}
\tr{\td{Sub-1G}\td{(need Tapo H200)}\td{--}\td{--}\td{Battery camera mesh}}
}

\p{The Apple Thread border router at \code{Game-Room.local} advertises via \code{_meshcop._udp} on port 49153. It runs Thread 1.3.0 with DefaultDomain. This is the Matter backbone -- any Matter-compatible device (including the planned Tapo H200) joins through this border router.}

\p{The Hue Bridge (bridgeid \code{ecb5fafffebec998}) runs Zigbee and bridges to HomeKit via the Apple ecosystem. It serves HTTPS on port 443 at \code{ecb5fabec998.local}.}
}

